    {
      "source": "target",
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Absolutely! The Circle of Fifths is a musical tool that helps you understand the relationships between different key signatures. Imagine a circle, with each point representing a key signature, and each step to the right is a fifth higher. If you start at C major, moving to the right, you'll land on G major, then D major, and so on. This circle helps you see how keys are related and how they can be easily transposed or modulated to.\n\nTo figure out what key signature a song is in, you can look at the chords used in the song. Each chord corresponds to a specific key signature. For example, if you see a lot of C major chords, the song is likely in the key of C major. If you see a lot of G major chords, it’s likely in the key of G major. The Circle of Fifths can also help you understand the harmonic progression of a song and how it moves from one key to another. Just remember, the Circle of Fifths is a helpful guide, but it’s not always perfect. Sometimes songs can be in keys that aren’t directly related on the circle, especially in more modern or experimental music. But for most traditional songs, the Circle of Fifths will be",
